body:
When CMake is used to verilate the project and the project HDL files contain dashes (-) in their file names, Verilator will generate C++ classes with dashes in their names, which is illegal.

The error does not seem to be rise when using `verilator` in command line.

Example of a generated file:
```C++
// Verilated -*- C++ -*-
// DESCRIPTION: Verilator output: Primary design header
//
// This header should be included by all source files instantiating the design.
// The class here is then constructed to instantiate the design.
// See the Verilator manual for examples.

#ifndef _VVERILOG_FILE_WITH_DASH_H_
#define _VVERILOG_FILE_WITH_DASH_H_  // guard

#include "verilated.h"

//==========

class Vverilog-file-with-dash__Syms;      // <-- ILLEGAL CLASS NAME
class Vverilog-file-with-dash___024unit;  // <-- ILLEGAL CLASS NAME


//----------
```

Verilator Version: `Verilator 5.007 devel rev v5.006-72-g4eb280601` (Git master version)

Minimal non-working example: https://github.com/Metric-Void/verilator-cmake-error

OS/Distro: Ubuntu/22.10 Kinetic
